04216nam a22006855i 9780823295388DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222000nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232953887 a10.1515/97808232953882doi  a(DE-B1597)626428  a(OCoLC)1322125552  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAW0180002bisacsh1 aBriffault, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDollars and Democracy :bA Blueprint for Campaign Finance Reform /cRichard Briffault. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (225 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tSpecial Commission on Campaign Finance Reform -- tForeword -- t1. Introduction and Summary -- t2. The Federal Campaign Finance System -- t3. Basic Principles of Campaign Finance Regulation -- t4. Recommendations -- t5. Conclusion -- tSources -- tAddendum: Separate Statements by Commission Members0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOur federal campaign finance system is in a state of disarray. The current regulatory scheme is not curbing, and may be abetting, the enormous increase in campaign contributions and expenditures. The enormous influence of major campaign donors on the process of government is a growing cause of national concern. The Special Commission of The Association of the Bar of the City of New York has spent the past two years studying the current system and developing a blueprint for reform. Composed of members with diverse political views and extensive legal and government experience, the Commission takes a fresh look at how to limit the undue influence of private money in federal elections. The result is a highly readable report that tells how the current system, established in the wake of the Watergate scandal, is being manipulated by monied special interests, and how the system can be reformed. The report addresses: how to develop a level playing field for candidates; how to limit the amount of money flowing into campaigns while allowing candidates to mount effective races; how to curb the use of soft money and issue advocacy while preserving the role of political parties; and how to structure a system that will restore public confidence in government. This account is must reading on an issue that is moving to the center of the national stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh1 aFeerick, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufman, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329538840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823295388423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823295388/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK